Food is to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 countries of the Eurozone, the price was higher than expected in November – after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg reports.
Official forecasts were down from just 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the American, British, and Canadian central bank, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered its interest rates, which they believe would favor rising commodity prices and a slight fall in unemployment to create a spiral of inflation.
The ECB aims to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two-percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the swing: one has to “negotiate” inflation in order to rule out later needs for action.
With 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a record 12-year high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Responsible for the rise in inflation in the euro area are the rising food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat ratings rose by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in food oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year – last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, but in 2009 it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 per cent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
