Disinfectants are saved in many places
More than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, which were due to improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overcrowding of the staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the containment of infections, according to the lead doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was admitted to the hospital after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection.
The victim of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but shortly thereafter the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not yet been carried out because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
Until 10 December of this year, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported from hospitals in 1094 to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the lead physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, but the dark numbers are likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in its nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well-healed.
However, if the agents are too high-dose or improperly applied, the well-responsive bacteria produce antibiotic-resistant, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
In particular, in patients with a weakened, or permanently malfunctioning immune system, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the daily life of the hospital.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi said - MRSA is just not there where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
“Such patients are isolated, the care staff wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment,” says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are being tested for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for the inhibition of the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
After this infection is prevalent in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients who were delivered and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, microbiological sampling is not so common.
Not least because there are no grants for this examination on the part of the state health fund.
Therefore, most cases only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
On the part of the European Union there are strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological examinations are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can be formed, but these directives are not always complied with by hospitals.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer among outpatients, or patients in basic care, according to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
Saved by the disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to the other by caregivers.
This is precisely why handwashing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by drip infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds barely lined up, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz goes on to note, unfortunately, in the financially less well-prepared hospitals, it even happens that when disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that exactly favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are found to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections in the grip causes health insurance to incur huge costs, so they are combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment in the government program, was maintained.
After the first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) as well as the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
