After more than 60 years of confidential treatment, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, documenting the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be seen until now, except with a humanitarian intention, that is, individual and name-related, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven states entrusted with their administration, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed in May 2006 to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Heikle Information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable research to be carried out, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the state of health of forced workers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which will be chaired by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CI).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public, due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Such as, for example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental handicap of some deportation victims.
The prisoner lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled for a practical reason after the war: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with a means of proof of their arrest, in order to give them the way to their emancipation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of personal requests.
However, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in accessing Bad Arolsen.
One must not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
