New fears about the Russian-Ukrainian natural gas dispute
A new price dispute is brewing between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe will be affected.
Most of Russia’s natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are led by Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is very closely observed.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for the natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
An earlier conflict between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be charged more, as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine has to pay 40% more for imports from Gazprom.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks,” Ukraine’s Economy Minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changing gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit charges [to Western Europe] via Ukraine.”
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom shortened deliveries to Ukraine.
This resulted in a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drove prices up dramatically.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the world’s largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
